# Component Rules

## File Structure
Every component lives in its own folder:
```
ComponentName/
  ComponentName.tsx          # implementation
  ComponentName.module.scss  # styles
  ComponentName.test.tsx     # tests
  index.ts                   # barrel export
```

## Props
- Extend the relevant HTML element interface where it makes sense (e.g. `ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>`)
- Spread `...rest` onto the root element so consumers can pass `data-*`, `aria-*`, `className`, etc.
- Always accept an optional `className` prop and merge it via `cn()`

```tsx
// ✅
export interface ButtonProps extends ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}
export function Button({ variant = 'primary', className, ...rest }: ButtonProps) {
  return <button className={cn(styles.button, styles[`button--${variant}`], className)} {...rest} />;
}
```

## Styling — SCSS Modules only
- Never use inline styles or CSS-in-JS
- Use `cn()` from `@/utils/cn` for conditional class merging
- Use BEM-style modifier classes: `.button--primary`, `.button--sm`
- Consume design tokens via `@use '@/styles/tokens/...' as *`
- Use CSS custom properties (`var(--color-primary)`) for theme-aware values

```scss
// ✅
@use '@/styles/tokens/spacing' as *;
.button { padding: $spacing-2 $spacing-4; color: var(--color-text); }

// ❌
.button { padding: 8px 16px; color: #111827; }
```

## Testing
- One test file per component, co-located in the same folder
- Use `@testing-library/react` + `vitest`
- Test behaviour (what the user sees/does), not implementation details
- Cover: renders correctly · user interactions · disabled/error states · variant/size classes

```tsx
it('calls onClick when clicked', async () => {
  const handler = vi.fn();
  render(<Button onClick={handler}>Click</Button>);
  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button'));
  expect(handler).toHaveBeenCalledOnce();
});
```

## Accessibility
- Interactive elements must be keyboard-focusable with a visible `:focus-visible` outline
- Form inputs must have associated `<label>` elements (use `htmlFor` + `id`)
- Use semantic HTML before reaching for `role` overrides
